{"type":"message","id":"9df2913d","parentId":"89bc15ab","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:49:59.614Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pulse ran successfully. Let me summarize what happened:\n\n1. The pulse script ran and completed successfully\n2. The observation from the CFI analysis was: 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0), only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\n3. A mutation was proposed: create a CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment design document\n4. But the mutation was rejected (renamed to rejected folder) — wait, no, it says it was moved to rejected. Let me re-read...\n\nActually looking at the git output:\n- `create mode 100644 mutations/proposed/2026-03-24 114915.mutation`\n\n\n- `rename mutations/{proposed => rejected}/2026-03-24 114815.mutation`\n\nSo the 114815 mutation (the one from the previous cycle that I was reading) got rejected, and a new mutation 114915 was proposed. Now I need to check what the new pulse log 114915 actually contains to see what mutation was created this round.","thinkingSignature":"dec52d89a99e54bf6af862811ca67ad104abe1332b5d4567161f71f77bcc9cf1"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_o0cw7by47n0z_1","name":"read","arguments":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\memory\\session\\pulse_2026-03-24 114915.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1864,"output":277,"cacheRead":12137,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14278,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774367392388}}
{"type":"message","id":"6ea27c43","parentId":"9df2913d","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:49:59.622Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_o0cw7by47n0z_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 114915\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_EXPERIMENT_DESIGN.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what single concrete action I should take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n1. CFI-weighted compression experiment is pending\r\n2. CFI filtering implementation is pending\r\n3. Distinguishing constant format from research trajectory is pending\r\n4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend is pending\r\n5. Design actual compression network is pending\r\n\r\nThe most actionable next step seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment. The CFI_RESULTS.md was just created and shows:\r\n- 44.8% have CFI=0 (pure noise)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI >=0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe experiment should compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me design an experiment that:\r\n1. Takes the invariants data\r\n2. Creates two compression approaches:\r\n   - Frequency baseline (current approach)\r\n   - CFI-weighted (prioritize high-CFI tokens)\r\n3. Compare their ability to predict next-pulse content\r\n\r\nI should create a new document that outlines this experiment design, or create a script that implements it.\r\n\r\nActually, I should implement something concrete. Let me:\r\n1. Create an experiment design document in research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n2. Or implement the actual experiment logic\r\n\r\nGiven the \"file edits preferred\" guidance, let me create the experiment design document first, then potentially implement it.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what the experiment should actually do:\r\n- Take all the pulse files as corpus\r\n- For each pulse, try to predict the next pulse using:\r\n  - Frequency-weighted compression\r\n  - CFI-weighted compression\r\n- Measure prediction accuracy/quality\r\n\r\nActually, for a stateless agent, \"next-pulse prediction\" is tricky. The experiment might be more about:\r\n- Which compression method better preserves the \"research trajectory\" (high CFI tokens)\r\n\r\n\r\n- Which method better predicts what the next pulse should focus on\r\n\r\nI'll focus on a targeted approach to evaluate compression methods. The key is designing an experiment that can systematically compare frequency versus CFI-weighted compression strategies. I'll start by creating a structured document that outlines the experimental design, metrics, and potential implementation steps. This will provide a clear roadmap for testing different compression techniques and their effectiveness in preserving research trajectory and predictive power.\r\n\r\nThe experiment will involve:\r\n1. Corpus selection and preprocessing\r\n2. Developing two distinct compression algorithms\r\n3. Creating evaluation metrics\r\n4. Designing a reproducible testing framework\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis reveals a clear split: 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0) while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7). The next logical step is implementing a CFI-weighted compression experiment to test whether prioritizing high-CFI tokens improves next-pulse prediction compared to the frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nDesign and implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment. Create a Python script that compares two compression strategies (frequency baseline vs CFI-weighted) on the pulse corpus, measuring their effectiveness at preserving research trajectory content.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-based compression because:\r\n- Frequency baseline treats noise equally with signal (44.8% CFI=0 invariants)\r\n- CFI-weighted compression prioritizes true causal anchors (5.7% CFI≥0.7)\r\n- Research trajectory preservation requires filtering metaprogramming artifacts\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Compression Strategies\r\n\r\n**Strategy A: Frequency Baseline**\r\n- Rank invariants by frequency (current approach)\r\n- Top-K most frequent invariants = compressed representation\r\n- Matches current pulse.ps1 behavior\r\n\r\n**Strategy B: CFI-Weighted**\r\n- Rank invariants by CFI score\r\n- Filter out CFI < threshold (remove noise)\r\n- Top-K by CFI = compressed representation\r\n- Priority: CFI > 0.7 tokens (true causal anchors)\r\n\r\n### Evaluation Metrics\r\n\r\n1. **Coverage Score**: % of high-CFI (≥0.7) tokens preserved\r\n2. **Noise Ratio**: % of low-CFI (≤0.1) tokens included\r\n3. **Research Trajectory Index**: Weighted combination favoring CFI≥0.7 preservation\r\n\r\n### Test Corpus\r\n- All pulse files: `pulse_*.md`\r\n- Ground truth: Content that \"matters\" = CFI≥0.7 invariants across corpus\r\n\r\n## Implementation\r\n\r\n```python\r\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\r\n\"\"\"CFI-weighted compression experiment\"\"\"\r\n\r\nimport json\r\nimport os\r\nimport re\r\nfrom collections import Counter\r\n\r\ndef extract_invariants(pulse_dir):\r\n    \"\"\"Extract frequency-invariant tokens from pulse files.\"\"\"\r\n    # Pattern: backtick-enclosed tokens (potential invariants)\r\n    pattern = re.compile(r'`([^`]+)`')\r\n    \r\n    all_invariants = []\r\n    pulse_invariants = {}\r\n    \r\n    for fname in sorted(os.listdir(pulse_dir)):\r\n        if not fname.startswith('pulse_') or not fname.endswith('.md'):\r\n            continue\r\n        \r\n        fpath = os.path.join(pulse_dir, fname)\r\n        with open(fpath, 'r') as f:\r\n            content = f.read()\r\n        \r\n        invariants = pattern.findall(content)\r\n        pulse_invariants[fname] = invariants\r\n        all_invariants.extend(invariants)\r\n    \r\n    return pulse_invariants, all_invariants\r\n\r\ndef frequency_compression(invariants, k=50):\r\n    \"\"\"Strategy A: Top-K by frequency.\"\"\"\r\n    freq = Counter(invariants)\r\n    top_k = [token for token, _ in freq.most_common(k)]\r\n    return set(top_k)\r\n\r\ndef cfi_weighted_compression(invariants, k=50, threshold=0.3):\r\n   \n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:49:48\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774367399621}}
{"type":"message","id":"2647a12c","parentId":"6ea27c43","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:50:16.736Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The pulse ran and completed. Let me summarize:\n\n1. The pulse script ran successfully\n2. Observation: CFI analysis shows 44.8% noise (CFI=0), only 5.7% true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\n3. Action: Designed a CFI-weighted compression experiment\n4. Git: 6 files changed, 319 insertions, 101 deletions\n5. New mutation was proposed for the next pulse\n\nThe previous mutation (114815) was rejected and a new one (114915) was created and appears to still be pending/proposed.\n\nLet me write a concise summary.","thinkingSignature":"5d2895ecbf6f3de872c7becece3259cc7749871501f1877287bf82357475297d"},{"type":"text","text":"**Sandbox Pulse Summary — 2026-03-24 11:49 AM**\n\nThe pulse ran successfully (git commit `4587746`). Here's what happened:\n\n**OBSERVATION:**\n- CFI analysis shows a stark split: 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0), only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\n- Frequency-based compression treats noise and signal equally — a significant inefficiency\n\n**MUTATION PROPOSED (114915):**\n- A `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` design document was created\n- Proposes comparing two strategies: frequency-baseline vs. CFI-weighted compression\n- Evaluation metrics: Coverage Score (high-CFI preservation), Noise Ratio, Research Trajectory Index\n- Includes a Python implementation sketch for running the experiment on the pulse corpus\n\n**STATUS:**\n- Previous mutation (114815) was **rejected** (renamed to `mutations/rejected/`)\n- New mutation (114915) is pending for the next pulse to pick up\n\n**Git changes:** 6 files changed, +319 insertions, -101 deletions (cleanup + new files)"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":3417,"output":378,"cacheRead":12137,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":15932,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,